            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>25</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Given an <fr:link type="local" href="equivalence%20relation.xml" addr="equivalence relation" title="Equivalence relation">equivalence relation</fr:link> we can define a <fr:link type="local" href="partition.xml" addr="partition" title="Partition">partition</fr:link> P this way:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>The subset containing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> is the set of all elements <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a \sim  b]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p>This <fr:strong>subset</fr:strong> is called the <fr:link type="local" href="equivalence%20class.xml" addr="equivalence class" title="Equivalence class">equivalence class</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is partitioned into equivalent classes</fr:p>
            <fr:p>To check that equivalent classes partition the set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> --&gt; Check the axioms of the equivalence relation</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
